data.Name: SIN3 project
data.Description:
Histone deacetylases (HDACs) play important roles in cancer (9-11). The FDA approved HDAC inhibitor,
suberoylanilide hydroxamic acid (SAHA), is used for the treatment of advanced and refractory cutaneous T-cell
lymphoma (CTCL) in patients with progressive, persistent, or recurrent disease (12, 13) and is part of more
than 225 clinical trials of known status (www.clinicaltrials.gov). SAHA inhibits HDAC catalytic activity by binding
to the active site of the enzyme (14). Inhibition of HDAC activity results in altered acetylation of core histones
and other proteins that cause changes in gene expression, resulting in cell growth arrest and apoptosis (12,
13, 15). However more recent findings from our lab and others suggest that SAHA and HDAC inhibitors have
broader, noncatalytic effects on HDAC complexes as well (1, 8, 16, 17), which dictates a change in thinking
about the mechanism of action of HDAC inhibitors. There is an urgent need to better understand the
mechanism of action of SAHA, which is crucial to the ongoing efforts to develop HDAC inhibitors with
increased specificity and efficacy (12).

Previous Objective: Our central hypothesis is that the HDAC inhibitor SAHA induces a dynamic rearrangement of the
Sin3 protein interaction network that plays a key role in the mechanism of action of SAHA. Our longterm
goal is to determine the mechanisms that control the protein interaction networks centered on HDAC1
and HDAC2 in normal and diseased cells and to determine the effect of HDAC inhibitors on these networks.
The overall objective of this application is to determine the mechanism of action of SAHA on the Sin3 protein
interaction network. The evidence for this model is based on our published biochemical and quantitative
proteomic studies on Sin3/HDAC complexes (16, 18-21), and our publications on the analysis of the effect of
SAHA on the Sin3/HDAC complex (1, 16). A comprehensive protein interaction network and analysis of the
SAHA-induced dynamics of this network will provide novel insights into the mechanism of action of this
important human therapeutic.

data.Name: Exhausted T-cell Enumeration Project
data.Description:
Pilot Project Hypothesis: 
There is a positive correlation between CA patients’ number of circulating ‘exhausted’ CD8 t-cell AND patients’ ability to respond to an immune based therapy (i.e., immune checkpoint inhibition). 
These exhausted CD8 t-cells should possessing:
A cell surface marker identifying them as exhausted (perhaps PD-1), &
An intracellular configuration that identifies their ‘activation’ status (i.e., Warburg mitochondrial configuration, as opposed to mitochondria undergoing apoptosis or OxPhos)
The numbers of exhausted CD8+ t-cells should be easily measured from peripheral circulation using a novel but simple cytometric evaluations of 2 to 4 markers of exhaustion (e.g., cell surface proteins PD1 and CD3 or CD8, and an image feature that recognizes mitochondrial organization (MitoTracter with Hoechst or LysoRed)).

data.Name: mESC_eRNA
data.Description: eRNA is short, unstable RNA transcribed at enhancer regions. Several recent studies suggested that eRNA itself might have an activating effect at target gene activation; however, the mechanisms that underlie its function are still not well characterized. In this project, I aim to investigate the role of enhancer RNA at enhancer activation and expression regulation. I hypothesize that eRNA performs its function by interacting with other RNA-interacting proteins, including transcription factors, co-activators, and chromatin modifiers, while at the same time, the expression of eRNA is also regulated by these factors, forming a feedback loop. I will use genomic approaches, including ChIP-nexus and NET-seq to test my hypothesis and study the role of eRNA at different cell types and development stages.
